{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> σέβομαι</b>, <br /> mostly used in <i>present</i>: <i>imperfect</i> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.197 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> σεβήσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “POxy.” 1381.202 (2nd c.AD)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἐσέφθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 164, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 254b, 3rd c.AD: Porphyrius Tyrius Philosophus “Vita Plotini” 12 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>feel awe</b> or <b>fear</b> before God,<b>feel shame</b>, οὔ νυ σέβεσθ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.242, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 293; τιμῶν καὶ σεβόμενος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 729c \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; σεφθεῖσα <b>awe-stricken</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. author] “Phdr.” \">Refs</a>] [same place]: rarely with <i>infinitive</i>, <b>dread</b> or <b>fear to do</b> a thing, σ. προσιδέσθαι.., ἀντία φάσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 694 (Lyric poetry); μιαίνειν τὸ θεῖον 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 69d; σέβεται καὶ φοβεῖται.. τό τι κινεῖν τῶν καθεστώτων [prev. author] “Lg.” 798b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: so with <i>accusative</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>to fear to do</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 2.4.12 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>participle</i>, σ. προσορῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 250e. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> after [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i>, <b>revere, worship</b>, Κρονίδαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 6.25; θεούς 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 921, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πάντων ἀνάκτων κοινοβωμίαν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 223; Λατώ 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 123 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Λυκοῦργον σέβεσθαι <b>worship</b> him <b>as a hero</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.66, compare 7.197; προσορῶν ὡς θεὸν σ. τινά 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 251a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>do homage to</b> Zeus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 937 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: generally, <b>pay honour</b> or <b>respect to.. </b>, θνατοὺς ἄγαν σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 543 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]; τὸ φίλον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 187 (Lyric poetry), compare “Ph.” 1163 (Lyric poetry), etc.; σ. τινὰ τύχης μάκαρος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Taurica” 648. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__2.b</b></Level4> especially of Jewish proselytes, σεβομένη τὸν θεόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Act.16.14, compare 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 14.7.2 \">NT+1st c.AD+</a>]; σεβόμενοι προσήλυτοι, Ἕλληνες, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Act.13.43, 17.4; σεβόμεναι γυναῖκες [prev. work] 13.50. \">NT</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> of things, τὰ βυβλία σεβόμενοι μεγάλως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.128; ὄργια 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 949; ὦ Πιερία, σέβεταί σ᾽ Εὔιος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 566 (Lyric poetry); τὸ σῶφρον αἰδούμενος ἅμα καὶ σ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 837c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>active</i> σέβω is post-[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], used only in <i>present</i> and <i>imperfect</i>, <b>worship, honour</b>, mostly of the gods, σ. Δήμητρος πανήγυριν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 120; πατρὸς Ὀλυμπίοιοτιμάν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 14.12; θεούς 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 596; Νύμφας [prev. author] “Eu.” 22; Ἅιδην 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 777 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; τἀν Ἅιδου[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 780; θεῶν θέσμια [prev. author] “Aj.” 713 (Lyric poetry), etc.\">Refs</a>]; rare in Prose, νομίζεται θεοὺς σέβειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 4.4.19, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 600 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but also of parents, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1377, compare “Ant.” 511 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of kings, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Aj.” 667, etc. \">Refs</a>]; of suppliants, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 151 (Lyric poetry); λέγω κατ᾽ ἄνδρα, μὴ θεόν, σέβειν ἐμέ [prev. author] “Ag.” 925; αἰχμὴν.. μᾶλλον θεοῦ σ. [prev. author] “Th.” 530; σ. ὀνείρων φάσματα [prev. author] “Ag.” 274; τὰς ἐμὰς ἀρχὰς σ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 744 (εὖ σέβουσι is uncertain conjecture for εὐσεβοῦσι in 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 338, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1320, “Tr.” 85)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σέβειν ἐν τιμῇ with <i>accusative</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 166, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 647a: with \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i>, ὑβρίζειν ἐν κακοῖσιν οὐ σέβω, i.e. τὸ ὑβρίζειν, I do not <b>respect, approve</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1612; τὸ μὴ ἀδικεῖν σέβοντες [prev. author] “Eu.” 749 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: rarely of a god, Ποσειδῶν.. τὰς ἐμὰς ἀρὰς σέβων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 896:\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —σέβομαι as <i>passive</i>, <b>to be reverenced</b>, ἡ δ᾽ οἴκοι [πόλις] πλέον δίκῃ σέβοιτ᾽ ἄν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 760 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ σεβόμενον <b>reverence</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.1101d. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> less frequently <i>absolutely</i>, <b>to worship, to be religious</b>, τὸν σέβοντ᾽ εὐεργετεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 725, compare 897; οὐ γὰρ σέβεις 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 745; κρίνοντες ἐν ὁμοίῳ καὶ σέβειν καὶ μή 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.53 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but in all these places an object should perhaps be supplied from the context. (σέβομαι probably originally '<b>I shrink from.. </b>', of which σοβέω is the causal; perhaps <i>cognate</i> with Sanskrit <i>tyajati</i> 'desert, let go'.)","strongNumber":"G4576","accentedUnicode":"σέβομαι","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0765","matchingForm":"ἀσεβής","stepTransliteration":"asebēs","gloss":"ungodly","_zh_tw_Gloss":"不敬虔","_es_Gloss":"impío","_zh_Gloss":"不敬虔"},{"strongNumber":"G2317","matchingForm":"θεοσέβεια","stepTransliteration":"theosebeia","gloss":"reverence for God","_zh_tw_Gloss":"敬畏神","_es_Gloss":"reverencia hacia Dios","_zh_Gloss":"敬畏神"},{"strongNumber":"G2318","matchingForm":"θεοσεβής","stepTransliteration":"theosebēs","gloss":"godly","_zh_tw_Gloss":"敬畏神","_es_Gloss":"piadoso","_zh_Gloss":"敬畏神"},{"strongNumber":"G4573","matchingForm":"σεβάζομαι","stepTransliteration":"sebazomai","gloss":"to worship","_zh_tw_Gloss":"敬拜","_es_Gloss":"adorar","_zh_Gloss":"敬拜"},{"strongNumber":"G4574","matchingForm":"σέβασμα","stepTransliteration":"sebasma","gloss":"object of worship","_zh_tw_Gloss":